Exercise 3.8.1

1. What is the problem with this plot? how can you impove it

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +

geom_point()

Answer: There are overlapping points, therefore unable have proper visual representation. This can be improved by adding slight noise with jitter.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter")

2. What parameters to geom_jitter() control the amount of jittering?

Answer: using position_jitter() we can pass width and hight

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(width =  2, height = 3))

3. Compare and contrast geom_jitter() with geom_count()

Answer: geom_count is usufull when we have discrete data and overplotting as it counts the number of observations at each location. geom_jitter adds noise to the overlapping data and combines smaller datasets.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_jitter()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_count()

4. Whats the default position adjustment for geom_boxplot()? Create a visualisation of the mpg dataset that deomnstrates it.

Answer: Default poisition for geom_boxplot() is dodge

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot(position =  "identity")

Exercise 3.9.1

2. What does lab() do? Read the documentation.

Answer: labs() gives variuos options to modify lebels in diffrent axis and title. It takes parameters for lable, title and subtitle

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(y = "Highway", x = "Car Class", title ="Hightway mgp by class")

4. What does the plot below tell you about the releationship between city and highway mpg? Why is coord_fixed() important? What does geom_abline() do?

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +

geom_point() +

geom_abline() +

coord_fixed()

Answer: The geom_abline adds reference line to a plot for visual comparison. the coord_fixed , keeps a fixed angle to compare city mileage against highway.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline() +
  coord_fixed()

4

Why is N^0 not missing?

Answer: all value of x^0 is defaulted to 1

NA ^ 0
## [1] 1

Why is NA | TRUE not missing?

Answer: for an or condition of one condition is true it will return true.

NA | TRUE
## [1] TRUE

Why is FALSE & NA not missing

Answer: For any & condition if one condition is false the return will be false

FALSE & NA
## [1] FALSE

Can you figure out the general rule? (NA*0 is a tricky conterexample!)

Answer: Any defaulted NA value is considered an infinity, therefore any expression against infinity will result in infinity. For boolean expresssion NA will result in FALSE, therefore and condition that is compared with NA will be treated as it was being compared with FALSE

NA * 0
## [1] NA

3 What does the one_of() function do? WHy might it be helpful in conjunction with this vector

Answer: one_of() is used with column names are vector or String, this will throw an error: select(flights, vars) one_of() is used to remedy this.

vars <- c("year", "month", "day", "dep_delay", "arr_delay")
